WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.980
Welcome everyone, to those in the room and those joining us online,

2
00:00:04.120 --> 00:00:08.080
to this major symposium, Clonal Hematopoiesis: Aging

3
00:00:08.300 --> 00:00:11.400
and Drivers of Both Blood Cancer and Solid Tumors.

4
00:00:11.880 --> 00:00:15.480
My name is Jyoti Nangalia. I'll be chairing the session.

5
00:00:15.580 --> 00:00:19.200
I'm a hemato-oncologist based at Cambridge University

6
00:00:19.220 --> 00:00:22.419
Hospital, but also the Wellcome Sanger Institute, where I do my research.

7
00:00:23.220 --> 00:00:25.740
We have three speakers today. I'm one of them.

8
00:00:25.900 --> 00:00:29.100
We have Siddharth Jaiswal, who I'll introduce first.

9
00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:33.700
He's a current associate professor of pathology at Stanford?

10
00:00:34.840 --> 00:00:35.320
Associate.

11
00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:36.940
Associate at Stanford.

12
00:00:37.860 --> 00:00:41.340
One of the first people, together with Ben, to describe the concept of clonal

13
00:00:41.350 --> 00:00:45.100
hematopoiesis. So we're really fortunate to have amazing speakers with us today.

14
00:00:46.220 --> 00:00:49.840
His lab focuses on understanding the biology of aging, of the

15
00:00:49.860 --> 00:00:53.740
hematopoietic system in particular, and how these mutations associated with

16
00:00:53.780 --> 00:00:57.520
clonal hematopoiesis contribute not only to cancer, but also to age-related

17
00:00:57.600 --> 00:01:00.060
phenotypes. So first up, we'll have Dr.

18
00:01:00.260 --> 00:01:03.940
Jaiswal, then myself, and after that, Ben Ebert. All right.

19
00:01:04.041 --> 00:01:05.840
Over to you, Sid.

20
00:01:12.200 --> 00:01:16.140
Thank you, Dr. Nangalia, and it's my great pleasure to be back at

21
00:01:16.200 --> 00:01:16.860
AACR

22
00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:20.040
presenting our latest work.

23
00:01:23.780 --> 00:01:24.940
These are my disclosures.

24
00:01:27.580 --> 00:01:31.460
So clonal hematopoiesis is a premalignant expansion

25
00:01:31.580 --> 00:01:35.500
of hematopoietic stem cells, typically due to acquired somatic

26
00:01:35.580 --> 00:01:38.480
mutations in a handful of driver genes.

27
00:01:39.860 --> 00:01:43.780
And we know from first principles, clonal hematopoiesis should be

28
00:01:44.080 --> 00:01:47.680
very common with aging. Thanks to great work from the Sanger Institute,

29
00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:51.980
we can estimate that there are about 50,000 to 200,000

30
00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:54.740
hematopoietic stem cells in adult humans.

31
00:01:55.740 --> 00:01:59.540
And we also know that these HSCs acquire about one protein coding

32
00:01:59.600 --> 00:02:03.540
mutation every 10 years. Which doesn't sound like a big number, but

33
00:02:03.620 --> 00:02:07.600
if you multiply these two figures together, you can calculate that by the

34
00:02:07.620 --> 00:02:11.021
age of 70, there will be about 1.4 million

35
00:02:11.300 --> 00:02:14.940
protein coding mutations within the HSC pool of each of us.

36
00:02:15.900 --> 00:02:19.660
And if just one of these mutations is sufficient to confer a fitness

37
00:02:19.700 --> 00:02:21.950
advantage to a hematopoietic stem cell,

38
00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:25.720
then these clonal expansions should be common with aging.

39
00:02:27.620 --> 00:02:31.260
And indeed, that is what we see. And so I thought it'd be useful to

40
00:02:32.040 --> 00:02:35.640
spend one minute just talking about the terminology of clonal hematopoiesis,

41
00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:37.120
because it is a bit confusing.

42
00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:41.820
So clonal hematopoiesis, as I mentioned, is any clonal

43
00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:45.760
expansion due to a fitness-increasing mutation in a

44
00:02:45.780 --> 00:02:46.880
hematopoietic stem cell.

45
00:02:47.870 --> 00:02:51.660
And we know that clonal hematopoiesis, by this definition, is ubiquitous in

46
00:02:51.740 --> 00:02:52.460
all humans.

47
00:02:53.660 --> 00:02:57.620
Clonal hematopoiesis can be further subdivided into CH

48
00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.140
with known cancer-associated driver mutations.

49
00:03:01.290 --> 00:03:05.200
So that's how we first identified this state, is by looking

50
00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:07.760
in genes that were recurrently mutated in heme

51
00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:11.710
malignancies, and then going back to healthy individuals to see if they had

52
00:03:11.740 --> 00:03:12.700
those mutations.

53
00:03:14.660 --> 00:03:18.400
However, there is also clonal hematopoiesis with unknown driver mutations, and we

54
00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:21.440
don't really understand why these mutations expand.

55
00:03:21.800 --> 00:03:25.690
But we know that this is almost as common as clonal hematopoiesis with known

56
00:03:25.760 --> 00:03:26.220
drivers.

57
00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:31.400
And then within the known driver clonal hematopoiesis space, there's

58
00:03:31.460 --> 00:03:35.380
what we have defined as CHIP, clonal hematopoiesis of indeterminate

59
00:03:35.460 --> 00:03:39.260
potential. That's based on a variant allele fraction of greater than

60
00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:39.980
2%.

61
00:03:41.120 --> 00:03:41.580
And then

62
00:03:42.660 --> 00:03:46.540
clones that are smaller than this are sometimes called micro CH or microCHIP.

63
00:03:47.800 --> 00:03:51.080
These are very common, because only a

64
00:03:51.140 --> 00:03:54.920
subfraction of these small clones go on to develop into

65
00:03:54.960 --> 00:03:55.760
large clones.

66
00:03:56.800 --> 00:04:00.790
And then within the CHIP pool, there's CHIP due to single

67
00:04:00.860 --> 00:04:04.730
nucleotide variants or indels, so think mutations in TET2 and

68
00:04:04.780 --> 00:04:05.660
DNMT3A,

69
00:04:06.640 --> 00:04:10.180
and then there's also mosaic chromosomal alterations.

70
00:04:13.300 --> 00:04:17.190
So surprisingly, there haven't been that many studies that have reported

71
00:04:17.190 --> 00:04:20.860
the prevalence of these different kinds of clonal hematopoiesis all in a single

72
00:04:20.921 --> 00:04:21.601
population,

73
00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:26.480
mainly because you need whole genome sequencing data to identify clonal

74
00:04:26.500 --> 00:04:28.360
hematopoiesis with unknown drivers.

75
00:04:28.400 --> 00:04:31.700
It's typically identified because there's an

76
00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:35.160
accumulation of passenger mutations, which doesn't occur,

77
00:04:36.420 --> 00:04:40.080
at least is not detectable from whole blood sequencing, unless there is an

78
00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:41.000
expansion event.

79
00:04:42.100 --> 00:04:46.080
But we've done this in a few cohorts now, and this is the prevalence

80
00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:49.640
of the different kinds of clonal hematopoiesis as a function of age.

81
00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:54.530
So you can see that in those under the age of 60, it's relatively

82
00:04:54.580 --> 00:04:58.140
uncommon, about 10% in total. And this

83
00:04:58.200 --> 00:05:01.960
rises to about 80% of all individuals who are age 90 or

84
00:05:02.020 --> 00:05:04.330
older have a large detectable clone.

85
00:05:05.380 --> 00:05:09.280
And you can see that clonal hematopoiesis with indels

86
00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:13.140
or single nucleotide variants is almost as common

87
00:05:13.240 --> 00:05:16.280
as clonal hematopoiesis with unknown drivers.

88
00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:24.360
And one of the bigger surprises in the initial surveys of clonal

89
00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:28.180
hematopoiesis was the spectrum of genes that we typically

90
00:05:28.260 --> 00:05:29.040
see mutated.

91
00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:34.000
And if you think about typical oncogenes, things like

92
00:05:34.020 --> 00:05:37.620
RAS signaling pathway or tumor suppressors, like

93
00:05:37.660 --> 00:05:39.960
TP53 loss of function mutations.

94
00:05:40.780 --> 00:05:44.240
We do see these in clonal hematopoiesis, but they're

95
00:05:44.340 --> 00:05:47.480
relatively uncommon. Only about 10% of the total.

96
00:05:49.320 --> 00:05:53.260
Instead, the other 90% seems to be genes that are involved in

97
00:05:53.340 --> 00:05:56.820
epigenetic regulation, like DNMT3A, TET2,

98
00:05:57.180 --> 00:05:59.740
ASXL1, or spliceosome factor

99
00:05:59.800 --> 00:06:03.748
mutations.And so why are these particular genes that

100
00:06:03.788 --> 00:06:06.768
don't seem to have an obvious link to

101
00:06:07.828 --> 00:06:11.008
oncogenes or tumor suppressors, why are they positively selected?

102
00:06:12.328 --> 00:06:15.928
And we hypothesized that we could make headway into this

103
00:06:16.428 --> 00:06:19.248
question by studying it directly in humans.

104
00:06:20.408 --> 00:06:24.028
And specifically, if we could identify a way to

105
00:06:24.088 --> 00:06:27.848
calculate the clonal expansion rate in a large number of people,

106
00:06:28.908 --> 00:06:32.708
we could do large-scale association studies to try to figure out why these

107
00:06:32.748 --> 00:06:34.588
particular genes are mutated.

108
00:06:36.608 --> 00:06:40.228
And so we developed a method that we call passenger approximated

109
00:06:40.428 --> 00:06:41.588
clonal expansion rate.

110
00:06:43.408 --> 00:06:47.028
So this is a method that uses the total number of passenger

111
00:06:47.128 --> 00:06:51.058
mutations in a clone to infer how old that

112
00:06:51.148 --> 00:06:51.688
clone is.

113
00:06:52.598 --> 00:06:56.568
So basically, these passenger mutations are accumulated linearly with respect

114
00:06:56.608 --> 00:06:57.068
to time,

115
00:06:58.168 --> 00:07:01.808
and so it's like a timestamp for when that clone was born.

116
00:07:03.868 --> 00:07:07.428
And once we know how old that clone is, we can infer how quickly it's been

117
00:07:07.468 --> 00:07:11.408
growing using a simple linear regression model, as shown here.

118
00:07:12.448 --> 00:07:16.228
And what we hypothesized was that the residual, so if you plot the

119
00:07:16.288 --> 00:07:18.948
passenger mutations versus the input variables

120
00:07:19.948 --> 00:07:23.838
for each individual, which is shown by a dot here, the residual, which is

121
00:07:23.868 --> 00:07:27.708
the difference on the y-axis from the line of best fit to their

122
00:07:27.768 --> 00:07:31.648
number of passenger mutations, that should be a measure of the

123
00:07:31.708 --> 00:07:34.128
fitness of that clone in that individual.

124
00:07:35.968 --> 00:07:39.128
And so we went on to validate this method in several ways.

125
00:07:40.488 --> 00:07:44.128
And one of the things that we found was that the specific driver

126
00:07:44.188 --> 00:07:47.768
mutation itself is a pretty large determinant of clonal

127
00:07:47.828 --> 00:07:48.268
fitness.

128
00:07:49.168 --> 00:07:52.668
So these are our PACER fitness estimates for the most common

129
00:07:52.728 --> 00:07:54.248
drivers seen in CHIP.

130
00:07:55.308 --> 00:07:58.868
These are all shown relative to DNMT3A mutations.

131
00:07:59.128 --> 00:08:03.088
And what you'll note is that most of the drivers have a higher fitness

132
00:08:03.188 --> 00:08:05.448
than DNMT3A. So DNMT3A,

133
00:08:06.288 --> 00:08:09.728
somewhat paradoxically, despite being the most commonly mutated gene,

134
00:08:10.388 --> 00:08:12.747
also has one of the lowest fitness scores.

135
00:08:14.508 --> 00:08:14.568
The

136
00:08:15.668 --> 00:08:18.948
highest fitness scores were seen in the spicy som genes,

137
00:08:19.068 --> 00:08:23.038
U2AF1, SRSF2, and SF3B1. JAK2 was

138
00:08:23.088 --> 00:08:26.418
also quite high. And then in the middle, you see a lot of

139
00:08:26.448 --> 00:08:30.148
genes that are common, TET2, PPM1D,

140
00:08:30.368 --> 00:08:31.988
ASXL1, et cetera.

141
00:08:35.108 --> 00:08:38.968
So we know that driver mutation is a major determinant of growth rate,

142
00:08:39.808 --> 00:08:43.728
but we wanted to know, using our method, what environmental

143
00:08:43.739 --> 00:08:47.568
and genetic factors may also drive positive selection of these clones.

144
00:08:51.028 --> 00:08:54.068
So we turned first to environmental factors.

145
00:08:54.328 --> 00:08:56.528
And this is data taken from the UK Biobank,

146
00:08:57.908 --> 00:09:01.808
as well as some other cohorts. So we first measured

147
00:09:02.188 --> 00:09:05.948
biomarkers or demographic factors that were available in this data

148
00:09:06.088 --> 00:09:09.688
set and asked, did any of these associate with clonal expansion rate?

149
00:09:11.328 --> 00:09:15.068
And you can see that of these commonly assessed demographic

150
00:09:15.128 --> 00:09:18.948
variables, including sex, smoking, diabetes, BMI,

151
00:09:19.568 --> 00:09:21.628
inflammation, and air pollution,

152
00:09:22.488 --> 00:09:26.368
only smoking was associated positively with clonal

153
00:09:26.428 --> 00:09:27.208
expansion rate.

154
00:09:28.308 --> 00:09:32.048
This was a little surprising given the amount of animal model data

155
00:09:32.108 --> 00:09:34.108
supporting things like

156
00:09:35.308 --> 00:09:39.248
obesity or inflammation as being drivers of clonal

157
00:09:39.288 --> 00:09:41.108
expansion, at least in mice.

158
00:09:42.348 --> 00:09:45.028
However, we did not see these associations in humans.

159
00:09:45.248 --> 00:09:48.448
The reasons for that difference are not entirely clear.

160
00:09:51.688 --> 00:09:53.468
We've also looked at this in other ways.

161
00:09:53.508 --> 00:09:56.768
This is a collaborative project with Alex Bick's group at Vanderbilt.

162
00:09:57.828 --> 00:10:01.688
And what his group did was to create polygenic risk scores

163
00:10:01.748 --> 00:10:05.368
for different protein levels that you might have in your body,

164
00:10:06.348 --> 00:10:09.988
and then asked if you have a higher genetic risk of having

165
00:10:10.008 --> 00:10:11.248
certain proteins

166
00:10:12.328 --> 00:10:16.008
circulating in your body, does that associate with clonal expansion rate?

167
00:10:17.328 --> 00:10:20.828
And what we found generally was that genetically

168
00:10:20.968 --> 00:10:24.768
predicted cytokine levels were not very predictive

169
00:10:25.568 --> 00:10:29.108
for clonal expansion rate. The one exception being there was a modest

170
00:10:29.128 --> 00:10:33.058
association between predicted IL6 levels and the

171
00:10:33.128 --> 00:10:35.308
rate of growth of DNMT3A clones.

172
00:10:36.488 --> 00:10:40.208
And then there were a handful of other TNF-like factors that were

173
00:10:40.268 --> 00:10:43.668
also modestly associated with DNMT3A clonal

174
00:10:43.848 --> 00:10:44.468
expansion.

175
00:10:45.668 --> 00:10:49.568
So overall, what our findings have seemed to indicate thus far is

176
00:10:49.628 --> 00:10:53.408
that of the measured environmental factors that

177
00:10:53.648 --> 00:10:54.668
we can assess,

178
00:10:55.548 --> 00:10:59.088
it's really only smoking that seems to have a strong correlation

179
00:10:59.308 --> 00:11:00.428
to growth rate.

180
00:11:02.288 --> 00:11:06.248
And so we then hypothesized that perhaps we could

181
00:11:06.288 --> 00:11:10.208
do a genome-wide association study or a GWAS to

182
00:11:10.288 --> 00:11:13.948
look for germline variants of clonal expansion rate to

183
00:11:13.968 --> 00:11:17.848
reveal genes or pathways that may be associated with

184
00:11:17.888 --> 00:11:18.968
fitness advantage.

185
00:11:22.748 --> 00:11:25.388
And this is the result of our first survey.

186
00:11:26.368 --> 00:11:29.328
So this was done in the TOPMed cohort.

187
00:11:30.048 --> 00:11:33.248
This finding has been replicated now in additional cohorts.

188
00:11:34.488 --> 00:11:38.148
And what we found was that there was a single locus that reached

189
00:11:38.208 --> 00:11:40.168
genome-wide significance in the survey.

190
00:11:41.408 --> 00:11:44.008
The lead polymorphism in that locus is called

191
00:11:44.228 --> 00:11:47.908
RS2887399. It's a single nucleotide

192
00:11:47.968 --> 00:11:51.288
polymorphism in the promoter of a gene called TCL1A.

193
00:11:52.488 --> 00:11:54.568
The reference allele is a guanine.

194
00:11:54.748 --> 00:11:56.568
The alternative allele is a thymine.

195
00:11:57.408 --> 00:12:01.128
And what we observed is that the alt allele was associated with slower

196
00:12:01.368 --> 00:12:04.128
clonal expansion in several

197
00:12:04.268 --> 00:12:07.888
non-DNMT3A driver genes, including TET2,

198
00:12:08.028 --> 00:12:09.888
ASXL1, and some splicing

199
00:12:09.968 --> 00:12:13.638
factors.TCL1A is an interesting

200
00:12:13.678 --> 00:12:17.118
gene because it has been studied in the context of heme

201
00:12:17.138 --> 00:12:20.618
malignancies before. It was originally cloned by Carlo

202
00:12:20.718 --> 00:12:24.618
Croce's lab back in the 1990s because it was found in

203
00:12:24.678 --> 00:12:28.238
a translocation in a rare malignancy called

204
00:12:28.318 --> 00:12:31.878
T-prolymphocytic leukemia. That's a leukemia of mature T

205
00:12:31.978 --> 00:12:35.918
cells. And this translocation causes the TCR alpha locus

206
00:12:35.958 --> 00:12:39.938
to come into proximity with TCL1A to drive aberrant

207
00:12:39.978 --> 00:12:43.658
expression of TCL1A in the mature T cells, and it's thought to be the causal

208
00:12:43.678 --> 00:12:45.478
driver of that malignancy.

209
00:12:46.398 --> 00:12:49.758
However, there was no known link between this gene and myeloid

210
00:12:49.778 --> 00:12:52.098
malignancies or HSC biology.

211
00:12:53.978 --> 00:12:57.498
TCL1A is a bit of an enigmatic protein in the sense

212
00:12:57.558 --> 00:13:00.038
that it's not really very clear what it's doing.

213
00:13:01.638 --> 00:13:04.218
It's a tiny protein. It's 14 kilodaltons.

214
00:13:04.578 --> 00:13:07.438
It forms an obligate homodimer with itself,

215
00:13:08.338 --> 00:13:12.058
and early studies show that it was able to bind to the PH

216
00:13:12.078 --> 00:13:15.838
domain of AKT and potentially activate AKT

217
00:13:15.898 --> 00:13:17.538
via an unknown mechanism.

218
00:13:21.318 --> 00:13:25.298
And so what we went on to show in our published work, through

219
00:13:25.338 --> 00:13:28.918
a variety of experiments, was that we think TCL1A is a

220
00:13:29.018 --> 00:13:32.958
major driver of clonal expansion in hematopoietic stem

221
00:13:33.058 --> 00:13:33.458
cells.

222
00:13:34.558 --> 00:13:37.978
What we showed was that the TCL1A locus is normally

223
00:13:38.018 --> 00:13:41.598
closed or lowly expressed in hematopoietic stem cells.

224
00:13:42.658 --> 00:13:46.618
And in fact, the only cell types in adult humans where TCL1A is

225
00:13:46.658 --> 00:13:50.478
expressed are B cells, plasmacytoid dendritic

226
00:13:50.558 --> 00:13:53.778
cells, and progenitors of sperm cells.

227
00:13:54.918 --> 00:13:58.518
And so in this sense, TCL1A might actually be a very good therapeutic

228
00:13:58.558 --> 00:14:02.258
target because you might predict that you'd be able to block its function without

229
00:14:02.278 --> 00:14:04.378
really affecting normal tissues very much.

230
00:14:07.778 --> 00:14:11.418
However, if you now acquire a mutation in one of these driver

231
00:14:11.458 --> 00:14:14.658
mutations that we showed was associated with the polymorphism,

232
00:14:15.458 --> 00:14:18.758
we believe that this de-represses the TCL1A locus.

233
00:14:19.678 --> 00:14:22.117
So now the gene goes from off to on.

234
00:14:25.438 --> 00:14:29.278
This promotes TCL1A protein expression and we think is a driver of

235
00:14:29.298 --> 00:14:31.338
clonal advantage for these mutations.

236
00:14:33.418 --> 00:14:37.318
And the reason we were able to find this serendipitously was that there happens

237
00:14:37.358 --> 00:14:40.498
to be a subset of the population that has a

238
00:14:40.738 --> 00:14:43.898
thymine at this TCL1A promoter at this SNP.

239
00:14:44.838 --> 00:14:48.738
And we think that having this thymine variant prevents the chromatin

240
00:14:48.778 --> 00:14:52.538
from opening and abrogates the clonal advantage, and therefore

241
00:14:52.578 --> 00:14:54.238
reduces prevalence of CHIP

242
00:14:55.198 --> 00:14:56.258
in these individuals.

243
00:15:00.558 --> 00:15:04.378
So what is the full spectrum of driver mutations in

244
00:15:04.438 --> 00:15:07.538
CHIP that might be associated with TCL1A?

245
00:15:08.338 --> 00:15:12.178
And so what we can do now that we have this polymorphism that we know is

246
00:15:12.187 --> 00:15:15.618
strongly linked to TCL1A expression, is to systematically ask

247
00:15:16.538 --> 00:15:20.398
what driver mutations are enriched or de-enriched if you have the T

248
00:15:20.438 --> 00:15:21.918
allele at this locus.

249
00:15:23.038 --> 00:15:26.878
And if the prevalence of the driver mutation is below

250
00:15:27.018 --> 00:15:30.898
the dashed line, we would predict that these

251
00:15:30.978 --> 00:15:34.858
driver mutations are somehow dependent on TCL1A

252
00:15:34.898 --> 00:15:36.198
for their clonal expansion.

253
00:15:37.308 --> 00:15:40.298
And so we did this in the UK Biobank

254
00:15:40.338 --> 00:15:43.738
dataset, and we replicated our previous findings,

255
00:15:44.718 --> 00:15:46.768
which were that ASXL1,

256
00:15:47.638 --> 00:15:51.528
TET2, SF3B1, and SRSF2 mutations were

257
00:15:51.538 --> 00:15:52.538
strongly depleted

258
00:15:53.758 --> 00:15:55.678
in individuals who carried this T allele.

259
00:15:56.358 --> 00:16:00.308
But we found a number of other surprising things, such as

260
00:16:00.418 --> 00:16:04.178
NRAS mutations, IDH2 mutations, and JAK2 mutations

261
00:16:04.678 --> 00:16:07.438
may also be depleted in carriers of the T allele.

262
00:16:08.458 --> 00:16:12.118
And furthermore, we found that clonal hematopoiesis with unknown

263
00:16:12.138 --> 00:16:15.938
drivers, so this large class of clonal expansions where we

264
00:16:15.998 --> 00:16:19.958
don't really know why it's happening, it turns out the strongest genetic

265
00:16:19.968 --> 00:16:23.498
hit, so if you do a GWAS for clonal hematopoiesis with unknown drivers,

266
00:16:24.198 --> 00:16:28.047
the strongest hit is in this TCL1A polymorphism, suggesting

267
00:16:28.078 --> 00:16:32.037
that many of these mysterious clonal expansions may also depend

268
00:16:32.058 --> 00:16:33.978
on TCL1A expression.

269
00:16:38.438 --> 00:16:42.038
So we think that TCL1A is a critical factor for the

270
00:16:42.058 --> 00:16:45.278
development of clonal hematopoiesis, and it was found

271
00:16:45.938 --> 00:16:49.668
using GWAS. And many of you in this room may note there have been

272
00:16:49.738 --> 00:16:53.718
many polymorphisms, many genes that have been linked to clonal

273
00:16:53.728 --> 00:16:55.218
hematopoiesis through GWAS.

274
00:16:56.058 --> 00:16:59.318
But what I would say is distinct about TCL1A

275
00:17:00.258 --> 00:17:04.018
is that it is the only gene of all the GWAS hits that

276
00:17:04.078 --> 00:17:07.798
goes from off to on in hematopoietic stem cells

277
00:17:08.118 --> 00:17:11.219
when a somatic mutation in one of these driver genes is

278
00:17:11.238 --> 00:17:14.949
acquired. And this suggests that this is not

279
00:17:15.038 --> 00:17:18.878
just a modulator of clonal expansion, but it may be

280
00:17:18.959 --> 00:17:22.738
a major causal driver, so the reason that these mutations are

281
00:17:22.798 --> 00:17:23.798
actually selected.

282
00:17:25.578 --> 00:17:28.338
And if this model is true, there are two predictions.

283
00:17:28.738 --> 00:17:32.598
So one is that ectopic expression of TCL1A should be

284
00:17:32.658 --> 00:17:36.598
sufficient to cause clonal expansion phenotypes in vivo, in a model

285
00:17:36.698 --> 00:17:39.918
system, for example, by altering key HSC

286
00:17:39.958 --> 00:17:43.358
biology. And a second prediction is that TCL1A

287
00:17:43.378 --> 00:17:46.918
expression should promote the risk of at least some

288
00:17:46.958 --> 00:17:50.358
CHIP-related phenotypes, such as hematologic malignancy.

289
00:17:53.058 --> 00:17:56.998
And so we decided we would like to study this in an animal system.

290
00:17:58.618 --> 00:18:02.438
And as many of you in this room know, there are many models

291
00:18:02.518 --> 00:18:06.358
for these common CHIP driver mutations, including loss of function,

292
00:18:07.558 --> 00:18:11.318
TET2 alleles, TET2 catalytic domain mutants,

293
00:18:11.538 --> 00:18:15.478
truncating mutations at the C-terminus of ASXL1,

294
00:18:15.578 --> 00:18:19.538
and then point mutations in SF3B1 and SRSF2.

295
00:18:19.698 --> 00:18:23.422
So these have all been built in mice.And they

296
00:18:23.462 --> 00:18:26.882
variably show a clonal expansion

297
00:18:26.942 --> 00:18:28.762
phenotype at the HSC level.

298
00:18:29.742 --> 00:18:33.122
The majority of these mice show things like anemia,

299
00:18:35.302 --> 00:18:38.222
but only a couple of these models actually develop malignancy.

300
00:18:38.662 --> 00:18:41.902
And when they do develop malignancy, it's typically at a very late

301
00:18:42.182 --> 00:18:42.722
stage.

302
00:18:44.742 --> 00:18:48.702
And we looked in all of these models, and in none of these models could we see that

303
00:18:48.742 --> 00:18:51.422
TCL1A became expressed in the HSCs.

304
00:18:51.722 --> 00:18:55.491
So unlike what we see in humans, if you introduce these mutations into human HSCs,

305
00:18:55.882 --> 00:18:59.782
TCL1A goes from off to on. It doesn't seem to happen in the

306
00:18:59.822 --> 00:19:00.142
mouse.

307
00:19:01.802 --> 00:19:05.502
One reason for that is that if you look at the

308
00:19:05.522 --> 00:19:09.402
promoter region of TCL1A, this is where the polymorphisms

309
00:19:09.982 --> 00:19:11.642
that I described lie.

310
00:19:13.402 --> 00:19:17.002
You can see that there is generally poor conservation

311
00:19:18.362 --> 00:19:21.562
between humans and other species at this locus.

312
00:19:23.022 --> 00:19:26.922
And so we think that maybe because the promoter is not really conserved at

313
00:19:26.961 --> 00:19:29.462
this region, mice do not have the same effect.

314
00:19:29.542 --> 00:19:33.142
So even if you put the mutation in the mice, it doesn't lead to the

315
00:19:33.162 --> 00:19:34.781
de-repression at this locus.

316
00:19:37.402 --> 00:19:41.182
And so to get around this, what we decided to do was to build a

317
00:19:41.222 --> 00:19:44.762
transgenic mouse model where we could enforce

318
00:19:44.822 --> 00:19:48.222
expression of TCL1A in a tissue-specific manner.

319
00:19:48.962 --> 00:19:52.702
And so we introduced the TCL1A human open reading

320
00:19:52.802 --> 00:19:56.462
frame into the H-11 locus. It's a safe harbor locus

321
00:19:56.802 --> 00:19:57.302
in mice,

322
00:19:58.282 --> 00:20:02.222
and the promoter is separated from the open reading frame

323
00:20:03.182 --> 00:20:05.402
with box stop lux

324
00:20:06.302 --> 00:20:06.742
cassettes.

325
00:20:08.402 --> 00:20:12.372
And so what we can do is cross these mice to various Cre-expressing strains to get

326
00:20:12.482 --> 00:20:15.882
tissue-specific expression of TCL1A in the mice.

327
00:20:15.922 --> 00:20:18.322
And so we have done this using Bav1 Cre mice

328
00:20:19.122 --> 00:20:20.722
as well as Tau1 Cre mice.

329
00:20:23.382 --> 00:20:27.042
And what we find is that these mice, for most of their life,

330
00:20:27.622 --> 00:20:28.882
look largely normal.

331
00:20:29.702 --> 00:20:33.671
So we followed their CBCs up to a year, and you can see that

332
00:20:33.701 --> 00:20:37.602
there's really no difference in the white blood cell count, in the red

333
00:20:37.662 --> 00:20:39.862
blood cell parameters, in the platelet counts,

334
00:20:40.862 --> 00:20:43.422
or in the differential up to nine months.

335
00:20:47.302 --> 00:20:51.122
We did note that by midlife, there was

336
00:20:51.222 --> 00:20:55.022
a marked HSPC expansion in the bone marrow of

337
00:20:55.042 --> 00:20:58.622
these mice, and this was particularly evident in the long-term

338
00:20:58.802 --> 00:21:01.092
hematopoietic stem cell fraction of the bone marrow

339
00:21:01.922 --> 00:21:04.302
and less evident in the myeloid progenitors.

340
00:21:05.822 --> 00:21:09.301
So we think that TCL1A, as perhaps is

341
00:21:09.362 --> 00:21:13.102
expected, does lead to some sort of fitness effect on the hematopoietic stem

342
00:21:13.182 --> 00:21:16.462
cells and causes some sort of expansion in this model.

343
00:21:17.302 --> 00:21:21.062
We've also done competitive transplants, where TCL1A

344
00:21:21.082 --> 00:21:24.322
was forced to be expressed in some HSCs and then competed

345
00:21:24.362 --> 00:21:28.202
against wild-type HSCs, and you can see that

346
00:21:28.322 --> 00:21:32.142
over time, the TCL1A-expressing HSCs take over.

347
00:21:32.322 --> 00:21:34.602
So there is this competitive advantage as well.

348
00:21:36.282 --> 00:21:40.142
In terms of the mechanism of why TCL1A may cause clonal

349
00:21:40.182 --> 00:21:43.262
expansion of these HSCs, that's still being worked out.

350
00:21:44.322 --> 00:21:48.202
But we suspect that there is increased proliferation, so increased

351
00:21:48.262 --> 00:21:51.622
cell cycling of these HSCs and also resistance to

352
00:21:51.762 --> 00:21:52.662
apoptosis.

353
00:21:57.142 --> 00:22:01.122
So, we thought that these mice would probably not have a very

354
00:22:01.162 --> 00:22:03.342
exciting phenotype beyond what I just showed.

355
00:22:03.422 --> 00:22:07.352
But much to our surprise, when we kept the mice alive for up to a

356
00:22:07.502 --> 00:22:11.462
year, we found that there was 100% mortality in

357
00:22:11.482 --> 00:22:14.991
the TCL1A transgenic mice. So you can see that by one

358
00:22:15.142 --> 00:22:18.902
year in both Cre crosses, all of the mice have

359
00:22:18.942 --> 00:22:19.222
died.

360
00:22:20.562 --> 00:22:24.022
And we observed there's a pronounced splenomegaly and a

361
00:22:24.062 --> 00:22:27.202
pronounced hepatomegaly, as well as an expansion of

362
00:22:27.382 --> 00:22:29.522
HSPCs in the moribund mice.

363
00:22:30.542 --> 00:22:34.442
The phenotypes at death range from pancytopenic, that's the

364
00:22:34.482 --> 00:22:37.662
majority of the mice, to marked leukocytosis.

365
00:22:39.342 --> 00:22:43.222
And we further characterize what are these mice dying of, and

366
00:22:43.282 --> 00:22:46.902
it looks like the majority of the mice are developing a myeloid leukemia

367
00:22:47.002 --> 00:22:47.592
phenotype,

368
00:22:48.602 --> 00:22:52.282
characterized by sheets of abnormal myeloid

369
00:22:52.322 --> 00:22:53.742
cells in the bone marrow

370
00:22:54.982 --> 00:22:57.262
that express an abnormal phenotype.

371
00:22:57.462 --> 00:23:01.162
They're Kitlow CD11b positive, so they're myeloid,

372
00:23:02.082 --> 00:23:05.522
as well as CD34 positive and negative for lymphoid

373
00:23:05.582 --> 00:23:06.122
markers.

374
00:23:10.102 --> 00:23:14.042
So is this relevant potentially in human myeloid

375
00:23:14.122 --> 00:23:17.922
malignancies as well? And so we've asked if

376
00:23:17.982 --> 00:23:21.882
individuals who have this T allele, the one that prevents TCL1A expression,

377
00:23:22.782 --> 00:23:26.642
do they have any alteration in their risk of developing myeloid malignancy?

378
00:23:27.482 --> 00:23:31.402
And we can see that indeed that is the case, that carriers of the T

379
00:23:31.522 --> 00:23:35.462
allele are less likely to develop any myeloid malignancy,

380
00:23:36.462 --> 00:23:40.382
and an especially strong protective effect for CMML, chronic

381
00:23:40.422 --> 00:23:41.822
myelomonocytic leukemia.

382
00:23:45.322 --> 00:23:49.292
And finally, we've asked, is TCL1A still expressed in the

383
00:23:49.382 --> 00:23:52.882
hematopoietic stem cells from patients with myeloid malignancies?

384
00:23:52.942 --> 00:23:55.522
And we've looked at this in a couple of different ways.

385
00:23:56.282 --> 00:23:59.942
First, using publicly available single-cell RNA-seq data

386
00:24:00.182 --> 00:24:02.422
from healthy or malignant hematopoiesis.

387
00:24:03.262 --> 00:24:06.982
We can see that healthy HSCs, as expected, there's

388
00:24:07.042 --> 00:24:08.922
essentially no TCL1A expression.

389
00:24:10.022 --> 00:24:12.862
However, if we look in the HSCs from patients with

390
00:24:12.902 --> 00:24:16.822
CMML or MDS, so each dot represents a

391
00:24:16.882 --> 00:24:17.582
single patient,

392
00:24:19.042 --> 00:24:22.732
we now see TCL1A is expressed in these HSCs, confirming

393
00:24:22.782 --> 00:24:26.622
that it may actually play a role in the malignancies as

394
00:24:26.662 --> 00:24:30.534
well as clonal hematopoiesis.And we've also

395
00:24:30.574 --> 00:24:33.554
looked at this at the protein level using flow cytometry.

396
00:24:34.074 --> 00:24:37.474
So this is gated on a HSC fraction.

397
00:24:38.274 --> 00:24:41.574
You can see that in healthy donors, there's, as expected,

398
00:24:41.974 --> 00:24:45.154
essentially no TACE1A expressed, whereas we do see robust

399
00:24:45.214 --> 00:24:48.394
expression in these high-risk MDS cases.

400
00:24:51.974 --> 00:24:55.814
So to summarize, clonal hematopoiesis becomes ubiquitous with aging,

401
00:24:55.894 --> 00:24:59.214
but the factors leading to positive selection of these drivers is

402
00:24:59.414 --> 00:25:00.674
incompletely understood.

403
00:25:02.294 --> 00:25:05.974
Of the environmental factors we've studied so far, smoking seems to be the

404
00:25:06.094 --> 00:25:08.074
strongest promoter of clonal expansion.

405
00:25:09.034 --> 00:25:12.764
And genetically, we think that expression of TACE1A seems to be a major

406
00:25:12.764 --> 00:25:16.354
driver of clonal expansion of clones of both known and

407
00:25:16.414 --> 00:25:17.314
unknown drivers.

408
00:25:18.334 --> 00:25:21.934
And we hypothesize that TACE1A may be a therapeutic target for myeloid

409
00:25:22.194 --> 00:25:25.814
malignancies arising from antecedent clonal hematopoiesis.

410
00:25:27.614 --> 00:25:29.854
And I'd like to acknowledge all the people that did the work.

411
00:25:30.514 --> 00:25:33.894
The majority of the studies that I've showed today were done by a very talented

412
00:25:33.994 --> 00:25:35.554
postdoc, Isaac Tingestdal,

413
00:25:36.374 --> 00:25:38.814
and an MD-PhD student, JK Gopalkumar.

414
00:25:39.614 --> 00:25:40.594
Thank you for your attention.

415
00:25:46.334 --> 00:25:50.234
Beautiful talks. Thank you. The talk's now open

416
00:25:50.274 --> 00:25:54.134
for questions. Can I ask people to come to the microphones because this

417
00:25:54.154 --> 00:25:57.834
is being live-streamed, and for those joining us online to use the

418
00:25:57.954 --> 00:25:59.594
QR code and ask questions

419
00:26:01.074 --> 00:26:03.614
via the online chat so we can ask the speaker.

420
00:26:05.314 --> 00:26:07.594
Hi, Tim Ley from Wash U. Sid, beautiful work.

421
00:26:07.774 --> 00:26:10.834
I must have been shocked to see those tumors arise in those mice late.

422
00:26:11.954 --> 00:26:15.454
The long latency suggests that there's either cooperating

423
00:26:15.514 --> 00:26:18.294
mutations. I wonder if you know what they are or whether there's some kind of

424
00:26:18.374 --> 00:26:20.994
transcriptional earthquake associated with escape.

425
00:26:22.234 --> 00:26:25.894
Yeah, Tim, great questions. So we are trying to

426
00:26:25.954 --> 00:26:29.374
sequence the bone marrow from these mice now to determine if there are any

427
00:26:29.494 --> 00:26:33.204
recurrent cooperating mutations that to be determined.

428
00:26:34.314 --> 00:26:37.823
The thing that is a little bit surprising is the very narrow

429
00:26:37.934 --> 00:26:40.554
window in which these mice all seem to die.

430
00:26:40.654 --> 00:26:44.603
So they seem to be pretty healthy up to about nine months, and then by 12

431
00:26:44.754 --> 00:26:47.394
to 13 months, they're basically 100% dead.

432
00:26:48.734 --> 00:26:52.674
So I don't quite understand at this point why that

433
00:26:52.734 --> 00:26:53.274
window

434
00:26:54.134 --> 00:26:57.634
is very short, and it would be a little bit surprising if they all

435
00:26:57.694 --> 00:27:01.394
acquired the same cooperating mutations within that time

436
00:27:01.474 --> 00:27:05.294
frame. So I'm starting to suspect it's some sort of

437
00:27:05.374 --> 00:27:09.174
epigenetic state or something else that goes wrong

438
00:27:09.254 --> 00:27:10.214
around that time point.

439
00:27:11.654 --> 00:27:13.614
Are they transplantable?

440
00:27:14.574 --> 00:27:16.214
Yes, they are transplantable. Yes.

441
00:27:19.654 --> 00:27:22.614
Very interesting presentation. I have a couple questions, actually.

442
00:27:23.274 --> 00:27:24.724
Now that you can measure fitness,

443
00:27:25.634 --> 00:27:28.574
if we measure the fitness of the non-clonally involved

444
00:27:29.114 --> 00:27:32.514
hematopoietic stem cells in a patient who has clonal hematopoiesis, are

445
00:27:32.594 --> 00:27:35.454
they as fit as normal or less fit than normal?

446
00:27:36.694 --> 00:27:40.434
Yes, a good question. So the method that I

447
00:27:40.474 --> 00:27:43.974
talked about, we can only assess the fitness of the

448
00:27:43.994 --> 00:27:45.114
expanding clone.

449
00:27:46.194 --> 00:27:49.944
So I think you're asking, can we assess the fitness of the other HSCs that are

450
00:27:50.014 --> 00:27:51.094
not part of that clone?

451
00:27:51.514 --> 00:27:54.954
I'm by no means an expert on this, but I was always wondering, is the clonal

452
00:27:54.974 --> 00:27:57.654
hematopoiesis the result of the

453
00:27:57.754 --> 00:28:00.374
background failing from aging?

454
00:28:00.694 --> 00:28:00.764
Yeah.

455
00:28:00.804 --> 00:28:04.314
So now you can see the clones because they are the only ones left contributing.

456
00:28:04.594 --> 00:28:04.754
Yeah.

457
00:28:04.954 --> 00:28:08.014
Or is it really that they are more effective, that's why they are

458
00:28:08.514 --> 00:28:10.454
succeeding more and becoming more prominent?

459
00:28:11.224 --> 00:28:15.014
The other question was, when we say they are more fit, is it because they are more

460
00:28:15.174 --> 00:28:19.064
constantly dividing or more actively dividing, meaning is it the amplitude or the

461
00:28:19.154 --> 00:28:21.134
time? Can we distinguish these two?

462
00:28:21.774 --> 00:28:25.674
Because we say it's fit, but is it fit as a result of the

463
00:28:25.774 --> 00:28:29.374
constant firing, or is it fit because it does a lot when it fires?

464
00:28:30.034 --> 00:28:32.134
Yeah. So for your first question,

465
00:28:34.834 --> 00:28:38.554
we don't know for sure what the reasons are.

466
00:28:39.354 --> 00:28:42.554
Sorry, could you repeat the first question?

467
00:28:43.134 --> 00:28:46.254
We've been always told in oncology, this is an activated mutation.

468
00:28:46.374 --> 00:28:46.454
Yeah.

469
00:28:46.474 --> 00:28:50.414
Okay? I'm now trying to ask, is it more potent, the

470
00:28:50.454 --> 00:28:53.874
mutant, or is it more constantly on, and as a result, you end up having more

471
00:28:53.954 --> 00:28:57.334
function? So here, the same thing, the fitness, is it because of more

472
00:28:57.434 --> 00:29:01.254
proliferation per unit of time, or is it proliferating more

473
00:29:01.294 --> 00:29:04.134
than normal, so it ends up being represented more than normal?

474
00:29:04.434 --> 00:29:06.094
Can we distinguish these two scenarios?

475
00:29:07.274 --> 00:29:10.094
So we could try to do that using the mouse models.

476
00:29:10.814 --> 00:29:13.934
So far, we have observed an increased proliferation rate

477
00:29:14.834 --> 00:29:18.734
using things like BrdU over short time

478
00:29:18.814 --> 00:29:19.194
points.

479
00:29:21.134 --> 00:29:22.614
But I guess we don't know, is that

480
00:29:24.174 --> 00:29:27.914
also true in humans or is it perhaps some

481
00:29:27.994 --> 00:29:31.874
sort of inciting event in the environment that promotes the

482
00:29:31.894 --> 00:29:32.644
proliferation,

483
00:29:33.534 --> 00:29:34.554
and when that

484
00:29:35.454 --> 00:29:37.404
signal goes away, perhaps the cells

485
00:29:38.974 --> 00:29:42.534
aren't proliferating as much? We don't know that for sure.

486
00:29:42.714 --> 00:29:44.374
One of the things that was surprising is that

487
00:29:45.434 --> 00:29:49.243
in the mouse HSC literature, it is believed that causing

488
00:29:49.394 --> 00:29:53.114
HSCs to cycle reduces their overall stem

489
00:29:53.194 --> 00:29:57.074
cell potential and fitness. So if you force HSCs into cycle,

490
00:29:57.114 --> 00:29:58.674
they kind of exhaust over time.

491
00:29:59.674 --> 00:30:02.434
But at least when you acquire this TACE1A gene

492
00:30:03.754 --> 00:30:05.354
expression, that doesn't happen.

493
00:30:06.854 --> 00:30:08.554
One quick last question, if I may.

494
00:30:09.614 --> 00:30:10.834
Sure. Hi.

