731
00:44:03.330 --> 00:44:06.550
And then what was really tough is to do the informatics.

732
00:44:06.610 --> 00:44:10.510
We have 28 million CpG sites per colony. We have thousands of colonies.

733
00:44:10.850 --> 00:44:13.620
Every time you try and interrogate it, it runs out of memory.

734
00:44:14.470 --> 00:44:18.270
So we needed to build an informatics pipeline for this, and which we now have.

735
00:44:18.600 --> 00:44:22.550
And so for every cell, effectively, we now have 50 million CpG sites, duplicate

736
00:44:22.590 --> 00:44:26.150
rates less than 10% for those who look at genomic

737
00:44:26.160 --> 00:44:29.980
technologies, that's really good, and global methylation rates that are completely

738
00:44:30.070 --> 00:44:31.210
biologically plausible.

739
00:44:32.390 --> 00:44:36.330
So this is our study now. We have about seven healthy donors from 17

740
00:44:36.390 --> 00:44:40.290
weeks post-conception to 77 years and six hematological

741
00:44:40.330 --> 00:44:44.290
cancer donors that include some of the patients that I have just shown you

742
00:44:44.350 --> 00:44:46.150
from the somatic mutation analysis.

743
00:44:46.950 --> 00:44:50.750
And we sequenced about 1,200 colonies with both whole

744
00:44:50.790 --> 00:44:54.590
genomes and methylomes. The idea is that we use the somatic mutation

745
00:44:54.690 --> 00:44:56.010
tree as the gold truth

746
00:44:56.890 --> 00:45:00.510
of the ancestry, and then we assign CpG methylation

747
00:45:00.550 --> 00:45:04.460
changes to the phylogeny. So for every CpG in the genome, we can

748
00:45:04.490 --> 00:45:07.410
say has it changed? Which cell is it changing in?

749
00:45:07.450 --> 00:45:08.650
When in life did it change?

750
00:45:11.530 --> 00:45:15.380
And just to give you a sense, most of the CpGs were in open seas, and some of

751
00:45:15.430 --> 00:45:18.590
them were in islands, shelves and shores, as you'd expect.

752
00:45:19.110 --> 00:45:22.890
And we treated each CpG as a dyad, combining the read

753
00:45:22.910 --> 00:45:26.230
counts from this with the read counts for this into one

754
00:45:26.330 --> 00:45:30.190
dyad just to increase our power. And we didn't

755
00:45:30.210 --> 00:45:33.670
find there was much discordance within a dyad, actually.

756
00:45:33.750 --> 00:45:35.670
Dyads changed together, which was good.

757
00:45:36.710 --> 00:45:40.310
And as expected, we had fully methylation predominantly in the open

758
00:45:40.370 --> 00:45:44.030
seas, mostly unmethylation in the CpG islands.

759
00:45:44.570 --> 00:45:48.420
And when you look in the women, these two donors, blue and purple are women,

760
00:45:49.180 --> 00:45:53.010
we're finding a lot of half methylation in the islands and the

761
00:45:53.050 --> 00:45:56.370
shores because this is X inactivation in the females.

762
00:45:57.090 --> 00:46:00.930
What's really interesting is X inactivation in the females is not X

763
00:46:00.950 --> 00:46:02.010
chromosome wide.

764
00:46:02.830 --> 00:46:06.760
It is predominantly at the islands, the promoter regions, and

765
00:46:06.790 --> 00:46:10.150
much less in the open seas, which was quite interesting for us to note because I

766
00:46:10.210 --> 00:46:13.530
just assumed as a hematologist, you see these bowel bodies

767
00:46:14.550 --> 00:46:18.400
on your blood films and you sort of think the whole chromosome's just

768
00:46:18.430 --> 00:46:19.250
compacted down.

769
00:46:20.430 --> 00:46:22.010
So we did some further checks now.

770
00:46:22.950 --> 00:46:26.830
This is a phylogenetic tree now on its side, and those

771
00:46:26.870 --> 00:46:29.810
in my lab will immediately be looking at that and going, "What's the age of that

772
00:46:29.930 --> 00:46:33.710
patient?" Because we're quite good at aging someone based on their phylogenetic

773
00:46:33.790 --> 00:46:36.810
tree now. So this individual's probably in their 50s.

774
00:46:37.890 --> 00:46:41.370
And each row here is a consecutive

775
00:46:41.430 --> 00:46:41.910
CpG,

776
00:46:43.010 --> 00:46:46.490
and red is methylated, blue is unmethylated, white is

777
00:46:46.550 --> 00:46:48.070
methylated but only on one allele.

778
00:46:48.810 --> 00:46:52.780
And every row here, every dot here is the

779
00:46:52.970 --> 00:46:54.810
CpG for all the different colonies.

780
00:46:55.390 --> 00:46:59.210
So this is a block of CpGs, and we can see that it's unmethylated at the promoter

781
00:46:59.230 --> 00:47:01.010
of CSF3R, which we'd expect.

782
00:47:01.870 --> 00:47:05.350
This is a line element. It's fully methylated across all of our colonies.

783
00:47:05.850 --> 00:47:08.290
And this is an imprinting control region which is nicely,

784
00:47:08.820 --> 00:47:11.850
heterozygosely methylated.

785
00:47:12.730 --> 00:47:14.130
So these sites haven't changed.

786
00:47:15.660 --> 00:47:19.290
And now we have the challenging task of assigning methylation states to the

787
00:47:19.330 --> 00:47:23.240
trees. So what we have here now is we take the reads that are methylated

788
00:47:23.650 --> 00:47:26.810
for individual tips, we take the full sequencing depth,

789
00:47:27.770 --> 00:47:31.610
and then what we're essentially asking is we convert this into a methylation

790
00:47:31.850 --> 00:47:35.840
state, methylated, unmethylated, heterozygous methylation, and

791
00:47:35.870 --> 00:47:39.630
we account for in vitro changes. In vitro, there might be some demethylation, there

792
00:47:39.670 --> 00:47:42.000
might be some methylation, and we correct for that.

793
00:47:42.920 --> 00:47:46.850
And then we're basically saying, what is the probable sequence of methylation

794
00:47:46.970 --> 00:47:50.930
states that's occurred from the tips all the way to the root so we can see

795
00:47:50.950 --> 00:47:54.230
what the most likely changes are using a hidden Markov approach.

796
00:47:56.170 --> 00:47:57.950
And what we found was really quite staggering.

797
00:47:58.030 --> 00:47:59.950
So I'm just going to talk you through this one example.

798
00:48:00.590 --> 00:48:02.630
This is a tree from an MPN patient,

799
00:48:03.450 --> 00:48:07.350
and the y-axis is the number of mutations, and they have about 800 mutations.

800
00:48:07.410 --> 00:48:10.110
They're maybe about, I don't know, 40, 50 years old.

801
00:48:10.810 --> 00:48:13.989
And there are two clonal expansions here with drivers, which I'll talk about later.

802
00:48:14.650 --> 00:48:18.170
And I've expanded the top of the tree, the first 50 mutations that you

803
00:48:18.210 --> 00:48:21.890
acquire before you're born. So we can see the top of the tree

804
00:48:22.070 --> 00:48:24.090
really clearly, otherwise it's really squidged.

805
00:48:25.250 --> 00:48:28.670
And you can see that this block of CpGs, these 33

806
00:48:28.710 --> 00:48:32.680
consecutive CpGs in a promoter of PLD6, the fact that it's PLD6 doesn't

807
00:48:32.690 --> 00:48:36.010
matter. Well, it might matter, but there are loads of sites like this.

808
00:48:36.610 --> 00:48:40.370
This has changed from unmethylated to methylated one, two,

809
00:48:40.490 --> 00:48:44.350
three, four, and maybe a few more times, and each of those has

810
00:48:44.410 --> 00:48:44.930
happened

811
00:48:45.930 --> 00:48:49.918
very early in life.Around 10 mutations, which is basically

812
00:48:49.978 --> 00:48:50.958
around gastrulation.

813
00:48:51.838 --> 00:48:55.728
So during gastrulation and very early in life, each cell is going,

814
00:48:56.118 --> 00:48:59.518
am I going to be heterozygously methylated? Am I going to be unmethylated?

815
00:48:59.618 --> 00:49:03.358
Am I going to be fully methylated? And it's choosing an epiallelic state,

816
00:49:03.618 --> 00:49:05.338
which we'd never appreciated before.

817
00:49:05.658 --> 00:49:08.958
And there are thousands of these regions that are changing early in life.

818
00:49:11.058 --> 00:49:14.558
So then we went back and said we can't consider each CpG change as an individual

819
00:49:14.678 --> 00:49:17.678
change because they're changing together in segments.

820
00:49:18.048 --> 00:49:21.558
So we went back and segmented the genome using various approaches,

821
00:49:22.058 --> 00:49:25.338
and only last week we decided exactly which approach we're going to be using for

822
00:49:25.358 --> 00:49:29.278
the study. And as expected, most segments that change together are in

823
00:49:29.318 --> 00:49:31.298
promoters, around two million segments.

824
00:49:32.278 --> 00:49:35.878
And in transcribed regions, about 75% of your promoters have these

825
00:49:35.958 --> 00:49:39.718
large blocks of CpG segments. And in the quiescent regions, they're

826
00:49:39.758 --> 00:49:42.998
mostly single CpGs, two CpGs that change together.

827
00:49:44.238 --> 00:49:48.218
And then we found so many more. So because I said that these are changing early in

828
00:49:48.238 --> 00:49:50.398
life, we went to our early samples.

829
00:49:50.438 --> 00:49:54.418
We went to our cord blood and our fetal samples to go, are they really changing

