00:50:22.078 --> 00:50:26.018
This site has happened so many times, and sometimes it's allele

839
00:50:26.078 --> 00:50:29.218
A that's methylating, sometimes it's allele B.

840
00:50:30.358 --> 00:50:34.318
And this site I find particularly fascinating because every time

841
00:50:34.358 --> 00:50:38.148
it's acquired this segmental allelic state, it's the same allele.

842
00:50:38.658 --> 00:50:41.808
Now, what I don't know is this the paternal allele or the maternal allele because

843
00:50:41.818 --> 00:50:45.598
they're treated differently early in life, particularly with

844
00:50:45.618 --> 00:50:48.058
methylation, but this is all work in progress.

845
00:50:49.138 --> 00:50:52.748
So overall, we have about 4,000 or 5,000 of these

846
00:50:52.758 --> 00:50:56.678
segments of CpGs that are at least five CpGs long changing early

847
00:50:56.698 --> 00:50:59.678
in life, and thereafter, the rate is much slower.

848
00:51:00.118 --> 00:51:03.578
This is very different to somatic mutations that are quite linear over life.

849
00:51:04.558 --> 00:51:08.318
And in total, we have half a million CpGs changing early in life,

850
00:51:08.938 --> 00:51:12.618
and then slower. Now, you may notice this here, that's so much higher.

851
00:51:13.198 --> 00:51:16.598
This is in an in utero DNMT3A R802H mutation.

852
00:51:17.278 --> 00:51:20.688
Its acquisition is associated with 200,000

853
00:51:20.818 --> 00:51:22.958
CpGs that have demethylated.

854
00:51:25.118 --> 00:51:28.498
So then we asked what's the rate of somatic methylation changes in life compared to

855
00:51:28.638 --> 00:51:32.158
SNVs, and late in life we have about 100 changes per

856
00:51:32.318 --> 00:51:35.678
SNV, but early in life we have about 10,000 changes.

857
00:51:35.718 --> 00:51:37.798
So this is just a regression model.

858
00:51:39.028 --> 00:51:41.298
So much, much higher than we ever appreciated.

859
00:51:42.398 --> 00:51:46.358
And when you look at the really simple question, do clonal hematopoiesis

860
00:51:46.478 --> 00:51:48.758
driver mutations impact your methylome?

861
00:51:49.638 --> 00:51:53.558
The answer is yes. So every dot here is colored by

862
00:51:53.598 --> 00:51:57.498
the donor, and these are the number of epimutations per branch

863
00:51:57.558 --> 00:51:58.098
of the tree.

864
00:51:58.958 --> 00:52:01.068
And you can see some are above the line here,

865
00:52:02.478 --> 00:52:06.138
and they're all associated with driver mutations, 1q+, DNMT3A

866
00:52:06.218 --> 00:52:08.778
Y66F.

867
00:52:09.678 --> 00:52:13.658
And for losses, it's the same, around 5,000 large segmental losses

868
00:52:13.738 --> 00:52:17.318
early in life, and the ones that are above the line are often our

869
00:52:18.038 --> 00:52:20.258
familiar driver mutation players.

870
00:52:21.778 --> 00:52:25.558
And this may be how some of these mutations are conveying their phenotypic

871
00:52:25.568 --> 00:52:29.318
effects on stem cells. We need to see what these sites are and

872
00:52:29.358 --> 00:52:31.438
perhaps what genes they may be associated with.

873
00:52:32.398 --> 00:52:36.227
But what's really more interesting to me is, are these epialleles

